The *ODF Toolkit* allows you to work with OpenOffice/LibreOffice Writer documents (OpenDocument Text with extension `.odt`) and their [textual content stored as zipped XML][1].

## ODFDOM allows editing without manipulating XML
 
The Java API allows you to straightly work with the specific XML-structure using an abstraction-layer, the OpenOffice Document-Object-Model (DOM). 

For modifying text you might be interested in elements of [Text Content][2], such as e.g. `&lt;text:h&gt;` for headings or `&lt;text:p&gt;` for paragraphs. These XML elements have been modeled as classes `TextHElement` and `TextPElement` respectively in the OpenOffic-DOM.


See the Quickstart example of [ODFDOM - The OpenDocument API][3]:
```
// Create a text document from a standard template
// (empty documents within the JAR)
OdfTextDocument odt = OdfTextDocument.newTextDocument();
// Append text to the end of the document.
odt.addText(&quot;This is my very first ODF test&quot;);
// Save document
odt.save(&quot;MyFilename.odt&quot;);
```

### Open
Either create a new using [`newTextDocument()`][4] or load existing using [`loadDocument(File)`][5] methods.

### Modify
Use the **Document Object Model (DOM)** of the opened document (e.g. `odt`) to add, remove or modify elements.
The DOM contains a tree structure with various nodes or elements (each representing a specific XML element).

For example to get the first paragraph text and replace it:
```
// get the root element inside ODF XML
OdfElement root = odt.getContentRoot();
// count the child elements of root
int childrenCount = root.countChildComponents(true);
System.out.println(childrenCount);

// get a paragraph and its text, e.g. the first
OdfElement firstParagraph = OdfElement.findFirstChildNode(TextPElement.class, root);
System.out.println(firstParagraph.getTextContent());

// modify the text
firstParagraph.setTextContent(&quot;Hello World!&quot;);
```
Used methods to work on DOM elements:

* [`OdfTextDocument.getContentRoot()`](https://tdf.github.io/odftoolkit/api/odfdom/org/odftoolkit/odfdom/doc/OdfTextDocument.html#getContentRoot())
* [`OdfElement.countChildComponents(hasTextElements)`](https://tdf.github.io/odftoolkit/api/odfdom/org/odftoolkit/odfdom/pkg/OdfElement.html#countChildComponents(java.lang.Boolean))
* [`OdfElement.findFirstChildNode(clazz,node)`](https://tdf.github.io/odftoolkit/api/odfdom/org/odftoolkit/odfdom/pkg/OdfElement.html#findFirstChildNode(java.lang.Class,org.w3c.dom.Node))
* [`TextParagraphElementBase.setTextContent(text)`](
https://tdf.github.io/odftoolkit/api/odfdom/org/odftoolkit/odfdom/dom/element/text/TextParagraphElementBase.html#setTextContent(java.lang.String))
### Save
The [`save`][6] method used is a special one for `OdfTextDocument` and accepts a String with the filename directly.

Also, any document that inherits from abstract `OpenDocument` has a [`save(File)`][7] method.


  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenDocument
  [2]: https://tdf.github.io/odftoolkit/api/odfdom/resources/OpenDocument-v1.2-part1.html#Text-Content
  [3]: https://tdf.github.io/odftoolkit/odfdom/index.html
  [4]: https://tdf.github.io/odftoolkit/api/odfdom/org/odftoolkit/odfdom/doc/OdfTextDocument.html#newTextDocument()
  [5]: https://tdf.github.io/odftoolkit/api/odfdom/org/odftoolkit/odfdom/doc/OdfTextDocument.html#loadDocument(java.io.File)
  [6]: https://%20https://odftoolkit.org/api/odfdom/org/odftoolkit/odfdom/pkg/OdfPackageDocument.html#save(java.lang.String)
  [7]: https://odftoolkit.org/api/odfdom/org/odftoolkit/odfdom/doc/OdfDocument.html#save(java.io.File)

