**Edit Aug 22th 2019:**

There is a new method recently added to StorageReference&#39;s class in the Android SDK named [list()](https://firebase.google.com/docs/reference/android/com/google/firebase/storage/StorageReference.html#list(int)).

To solve this, you need to loop over the `ListResult` and call `getDownloadUrl()` to get the download URLs of each file. Remember that `getDownloadUrl()` method is asynchronous, so it returns a `Task` object. See below for details. I have even written an article regarding this topic called:

* [How to upload an image to Cloud Storage and save the URL in Firestore?][1]

---
In order to get the download url, you need to use `addOnSuccessListener`, like in the following lines of code:

    uploadTask.addOnSuccessListener(new OnSuccessListener&lt;UploadTask.TaskSnapshot&gt;() {
        @Override
        public void onSuccess(UploadTask.TaskSnapshot taskSnapshot) {
            storageRef.getDownloadUrl().addOnSuccessListener(new OnSuccessListener&lt;Uri&gt;() {
                @Override
                public void onSuccess(Uri uri) {
                    String url = uri.toString();

                    //Do what you need to do with url
                }
            });
        }
    });

As in the [Firebase release notes](https://firebase.google.com/support/release-notes/android) on May 23, 2018 is mentioned that:

&gt; Cloud Storage version 16.0.1
&gt;
&gt; Removed the deprecated StorageMetadata.getDownloadUrl() and UploadTask.TaskSnapshot.getDownloadUrl() methods. To get a current download URL, use StorageReference.getDownloadUr().

So now when calling [getDownloadUrl()](https://firebase.google.com/docs/reference/android/com/google/firebase/storage/StorageReference.html#getDownloadUrl()) on a [StorageReference](https://firebase.google.com/docs/reference/android/com/google/firebase/storage/StorageReference) object it returns a `Task` object and **not** an Uri object anymore.

Please also rememeber, neither the success listener nor the failure listener (if you intend to use it), will be called if your device cannot reach Firebase Storage backend. The success/failure listeners will only be called once the data is committed to, or rejected by the Firebase servers.


  [1]: https://medium.com/firebase-tips-tricks/how-to-upload-an-image-to-cloud-storage-and-save-the-url-in-firestore-42711ca1df46

